7903 // #include <nlohmann/detail/exceptions.hpp>
7904 
7905 // #include <nlohmann/detail/value_t.hpp>
7906 
7907 namespace nlohmann {
7908  template <typename BasicJsonType>
7909  class json_pointer {
7910  // allow basic_json to access private members
7911  NLOHMANN_BASIC_JSON_TPL_DECLARATION
7912  friend class basic_json;
7913 
7914  public:
7936  explicit json_pointer(const std::string &s = "") : reference_tokens(split(s)) {
7937  }
7938 
7954  std::string to_string() const noexcept {
7955  return std::accumulate(reference_tokens.begin(), reference_tokens.end(), std::string{},
7956  [](const std::string &a, const std::string &b) { return a + "/" + escape(b); });
7957  }
7958 
7960  operator std::string() const {
7961  return to_string();
7962  }
7963 
7971  static int array_index(const std::string &s) {
7972  std::size_t processed_chars = 0;
7973  const int res = std::stoi(s, &processed_chars);
7974 
7975  // check if the string was completely read
7976  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(processed_chars != s.size())) {
7977  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(404, "unresolved reference token '" + s + "'"));
7978  }
7979 
7980  return res;
7981  }
7982 
7983  private:
7988  std::string pop_back() {
7989  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(is_root())) {
7990  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(405, "JSON pointer has no parent"));
7991  }
7992 
7993  auto last = reference_tokens.back();
7994  reference_tokens.pop_back();
7995  return last;
7996  }
7997 
7999  bool is_root() const {
8000  return reference_tokens.empty();
8001  }
8002 
8003  json_pointer top() const {
8004  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(is_root())) {
8005  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(405, "JSON pointer has no parent"));
8006  }
8007 
8008  json_pointer result = *this;
8009  result.reference_tokens = {reference_tokens[0]};
8010  return result;
8011  }
8012 
8021  BasicJsonType &get_and_create(BasicJsonType &j) const {
8022  using size_type = typename BasicJsonType::size_type;
8023  auto result = &j;
8024 
8025  // in case no reference tokens exist, return a reference to the JSON value
8026  // j which will be overwritten by a primitive value
8027  for (const auto &reference_token : reference_tokens) {
8028  switch (result->m_type) {
8029  case detail::value_t::null: {
8030  if (reference_token == "0") {
8031  // start a new array if reference token is 0
8032  result = &result->operator[](0);
8033  } else {
8034  // start a new object otherwise
8035  result = &result->operator[](reference_token);
8036  }
8037  break;
8038  }
8039 
8040  case detail::value_t::object: {
8041  // create an entry in the object
8042  result = &result->operator[](reference_token);
8043  break;
8044  }
8045 
8046  case detail::value_t::array: {
8047  // create an entry in the array
8048  JSON_TRY {
8049  result = &result->operator[](static_cast<size_type>(array_index(reference_token)));
8050  }
8051  JSON_CATCH(std::invalid_argument &) {
8052  JSON_THROW(detail::parse_error::create(109, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' is not a number"));
8053  }
8054  break;
8055  }
8056 
8057  /*
8058  The following code is only reached if there exists a reference
8059  token _and_ the current value is primitive. In this case, we have
8060  an error situation, because primitive values may only occur as
8061  single value; that is, with an empty list of reference tokens.
8062  */
8063  default:
8064  JSON_THROW(detail::type_error::create(313, "invalid value to unflatten"));
8065  }
8066  }
8067 
8068  return *result;
8069  }
8070 
8090  BasicJsonType &get_unchecked(BasicJsonType *ptr) const {
8091  using size_type = typename BasicJsonType::size_type;
8092  for (const auto &reference_token : reference_tokens) {
8093  // convert null values to arrays or objects before continuing
8094  if (ptr->m_type == detail::value_t::null) {
8095  // check if reference token is a number
8096  const bool nums = std::all_of(reference_token.begin(), reference_token.end(),
8097  [](const char x) { return (x >= '0' and x <= '9'); });
8098 
8099  // change value to array for numbers or "-" or to object otherwise
8100  *ptr = (nums or reference_token == "-") ? detail::value_t::array : detail::value_t::object;
8101  }
8102 
8103  switch (ptr->m_type) {
8104  case detail::value_t::object: {
8105  // use unchecked object access
8106  ptr = &ptr->operator[](reference_token);
8107  break;
8108  }
8109 
8110  case detail::value_t::array: {
8111  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
8112  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')) {
8113  JSON_THROW(
8114  detail::parse_error::create(106, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' must not begin with '0'"));
8115  }
8116 
8117  if (reference_token == "-") {
8118  // explicitly treat "-" as index beyond the end
8119  ptr = &ptr->operator[](ptr->m_value.array->size());
8120  } else {
8121  // convert array index to number; unchecked access
8122  JSON_TRY {
8123  ptr = &ptr->operator[](static_cast<size_type>(array_index(reference_token)));
8124  }
8125  JSON_CATCH(std::invalid_argument &) {
8126  JSON_THROW(detail::parse_error::create(109, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' is not a number"));
8127  }
8128  }
8129  break;
8130  }
8131 
8132  default:
8133  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(404, "unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'"));
8134  }
8135  }
8136 
8137  return *ptr;
8138  }
8139 
8146  BasicJsonType &get_checked(BasicJsonType *ptr) const {
8147  using size_type = typename BasicJsonType::size_type;
8148  for (const auto &reference_token : reference_tokens) {
8149  switch (ptr->m_type) {
8150  case detail::value_t::object: {
8151  // note: at performs range check
8152  ptr = &ptr->at(reference_token);
8153  break;
8154  }
8155 
8156  case detail::value_t::array: {
8157  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_token == "-")) {
8158  // "-" always fails the range check
8159  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(
8160  402, "array index '-' (" + std::to_string(ptr->m_value.array->size()) + ") is out of range"));
8161  }
8162 
8163  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
8164  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')) {
8165  JSON_THROW(
8166  detail::parse_error::create(106, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' must not begin with '0'"));
8167  }
8168 
8169  // note: at performs range check
8170  JSON_TRY {
8171  ptr = &ptr->at(static_cast<size_type>(array_index(reference_token)));
8172  }
8173  JSON_CATCH(std::invalid_argument &) {
8174  JSON_THROW(detail::parse_error::create(109, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' is not a number"));
8175  }
8176  break;
8177  }
8178 
8179  default:
8180  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(404, "unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'"));
8181  }
8182  }
8183 
8184  return *ptr;
8185  }
8186 
8200  const BasicJsonType &get_unchecked(const BasicJsonType *ptr) const {
8201  using size_type = typename BasicJsonType::size_type;
8202  for (const auto &reference_token : reference_tokens) {
8203  switch (ptr->m_type) {
8204  case detail::value_t::object: {
8205  // use unchecked object access
8206  ptr = &ptr->operator[](reference_token);
8207  break;
8208  }
8209 
8210  case detail::value_t::array: {
8211  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_token == "-")) {
8212  // "-" cannot be used for const access
8213  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(
8214  402, "array index '-' (" + std::to_string(ptr->m_value.array->size()) + ") is out of range"));
8215  }
8216 
8217  // error condition (cf. RFC 6901, Sect. 4)
8218  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')) {
8219  JSON_THROW(
8220  detail::parse_error::create(106, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' must not begin with '0'"));
8221  }
8222 
8223  // use unchecked array access
8224  JSON_TRY {
8225  ptr = &ptr->operator[](static_cast<size_type>(array_index(reference_token)));
8226  }
8227  JSON_CATCH(std::invalid_argument &) {
8228  JSON_THROW(detail::parse_error::create(109, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' is not a number"));
8229  }
8230  break;
8231  }
8232 
8233  default:
8234  JSON_THROW(detail::out_of_range::create(404, "unresolved reference token '" + reference_token + "'"));
8235  }
8236  }
8237 
8238  return *ptr;
8239  }
8240 
8247  const BasicJsonType &get_checked(const BasicJsonType *ptr) const {
8248  using size_type = typename BasicJsonType::size_type;
8249  for (const auto &reference_token : reference_tokens) {
8250  switch (ptr->m_type) {
8251  case detail::value_t::object: {
8252  // note: at performs range check
8253  ptr = &ptr->at(reference_token);
8254  break;

8262  }

8265  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_token.size() > 1 and reference_token[0] == '0')) {
8266  JSON_THROW(
8267  detail::parse_error::create(106, 0, "array index '" + reference_token + "' must not begin with '0'"));
8268  }

8276  }

8287 
8297  static std::vector<std::string> split(const std::string &reference_string) {
8298  std::vector<std::string> result;
8299 
8300  // special case: empty reference string -> no reference tokens
8301  if (reference_string.empty()) {
8302  return result;
8303  }
8304 
8305  // check if nonempty reference string begins with slash
8306  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(reference_string[0] != '/')) {
8307  JSON_THROW(detail::parse_error::create(107, 1, "JSON pointer must be empty or begin with '/' - was: '" +
8308  reference_string + "'"));
8309  }
8310 
8311  // extract the reference tokens:
8312  // - slash: position of the last read slash (or end of string)
8313  // - start: position after the previous slash
8314  for (
8315  // search for the first slash after the first character
8316  std::size_t slash = reference_string.find_first_of('/', 1),
8317  // set the beginning of the first reference token
8318  start = 1;
8319  // we can stop if start == string::npos+1 = 0
8320  start != 0;
8321  // set the beginning of the next reference token
8322  // (will eventually be 0 if slash == std::string::npos)
8323  start = slash + 1,
8324  // find next slash
8325  slash = reference_string.find_first_of('/', start)) {
8326  // use the text between the beginning of the reference token
8327  // (start) and the last slash (slash).
8328  auto reference_token = reference_string.substr(start, slash - start);
8329 
8330  // check reference tokens are properly escaped
8331  for (std::size_t pos = reference_token.find_first_of('~'); pos != std::string::npos;
8332  pos = reference_token.find_first_of('~', pos + 1)) {
8333  assert(reference_token[pos] == '~');
8334 
8335  // ~ must be followed by 0 or 1
8336  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(pos == reference_token.size() - 1 or
8337  (reference_token[pos + 1] != '0' and reference_token[pos + 1] != '1'))) {
8338  JSON_THROW(detail::parse_error::create(108, 0, "escape character '~' must be followed with '0' or '1'"));
8339  }
8340  }
8341 
8342  // finally, store the reference token
8343  unescape(reference_token);
8344  result.push_back(reference_token);
8345  }
8346 
8347  return result;
8348  }
8349 
8363  static void replace_substring(std::string &s, const std::string &f, const std::string &t) {
8364  assert(not f.empty());
8365  for (auto pos = s.find(f); // find first occurrence of f
8366  pos != std::string::npos; // make sure f was found
8367  s.replace(pos, f.size(), t), // replace with t, and
8368  pos = s.find(f, pos + t.size())) // find next occurrence of f
8369  {
8370  }
8371  }
8372 
8374  static std::string escape(std::string s) {
8375  replace_substring(s, "~", "~0");
8376  replace_substring(s, "/", "~1");
8377  return s;
8378  }
8379 
8381  static void unescape(std::string &s) {
8382  replace_substring(s, "~1", "/");
8383  replace_substring(s, "~0", "~");
8384  }
8385 
8393  static void flatten(const std::string &reference_string, const BasicJsonType &value, BasicJsonType &result) {
8394  switch (value.m_type) {
8395  case detail::value_t::array: {
8396  if (value.m_value.array->empty()) {
8397  // flatten empty array as null
8398  result[reference_string] = nullptr;
8399  } else {
8400  // iterate array and use index as reference string
8401  for (std::size_t i = 0; i < value.m_value.array->size(); ++i) {
8402  flatten(reference_string + "/" + std::to_string(i), value.m_value.array->operator[](i), result);
8403  }
8404  }
8405  break;
8406  }
8407 
8408  case detail::value_t::object: {
8409  if (value.m_value.object->empty()) {
8410  // flatten empty object as null
8411  result[reference_string] = nullptr;
8412  } else {
8413  // iterate object and use keys as reference string
8414  for (const auto &element : *value.m_value.object) {
8415  flatten(reference_string + "/" + escape(element.first), element.second, result);
8416  }
8417  }
8418  break;
8419  }
8420 
8421  default: {
8422  // add primitive value with its reference string
8423  result[reference_string] = value;
8424  break;
8425  }
8426  }
8427  }
8428 
8439  static BasicJsonType unflatten(const BasicJsonType &value) {
8440  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not value.is_object())) {
8441  JSON_THROW(detail::type_error::create(314, "only objects can be unflattened"));
8442  }
8443 
8444  BasicJsonType result;
8445 
8446  // iterate the JSON object values
8447  for (const auto &element : *value.m_value.object) {
8448  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not element.second.is_primitive())) {
8449  JSON_THROW(detail::type_error::create(315, "values in object must be primitive"));
8450  }
8451 
8452  // assign value to reference pointed to by JSON pointer; Note that if
8453  // the JSON pointer is "" (i.e., points to the whole value), function
8454  // get_and_create returns a reference to result itself. An assignment
8455  // will then create a primitive value.
8456  json_pointer(element.first).get_and_create(result) = element.second;
8457  }
8458 
8459  return result;
8460  }
8461 
8462  friend bool operator==(json_pointer const &lhs, json_pointer const &rhs) noexcept {
8463  return (lhs.reference_tokens == rhs.reference_tokens);
8464  }
8465 
8466  friend bool operator!=(json_pointer const &lhs, json_pointer const &rhs) noexcept {
8467  return not(lhs == rhs);
8468  }
8469 
8471  std::vector<std::string> reference_tokens;
8472  };
8473 }

8813 // JSON value data types //

8821 #if defined(JSON_HAS_CPP_14)
8822  // Use transparent comparator if possible, combined with perfect forwarding
8823  // on find() and count() calls prevents unnecessary string construction.

8912  using object_t =

9253  private:
9255  template <typename T, typename... Args>
9256  static T *create(Args &&... args) {
9257  AllocatorType<T> alloc;
9258  using AllocatorTraits = std::allocator_traits<AllocatorType<T>>;
9259 
9260  auto deleter = [&](T *object) { AllocatorTraits::deallocate(alloc, object, 1); };
9261  std::unique_ptr<T, decltype(deleter)> object(AllocatorTraits::allocate(alloc, 1), deleter);
9262  AllocatorTraits::construct(alloc, object.get(), std::forward<Args>(args)...);
9263  assert(object != nullptr);
9264  return object.release();
9265  }

9295  union json_value {
9297  object_t *object;
9299  array_t *array;
9301  string_t *string;
9303  boolean_t boolean;
9305  number_integer_t number_integer;
9307  number_unsigned_t number_unsigned;
9309  number_float_t number_float;
9310 
9312  json_value() = default;
9314  json_value(boolean_t v) noexcept : boolean(v) {
9315  }
9317  json_value(number_integer_t v) noexcept : number_integer(v) {
9318  }
9320  json_value(number_unsigned_t v) noexcept : number_unsigned(v) {
9321  }
9323  json_value(number_float_t v) noexcept : number_float(v) {
9324  }
9326  json_value(value_t t) {
9327  switch (t) {
9328  case value_t::object: {
9329  object = create<object_t>();
9330  break;
9331  }
9332 
9333  case value_t::array: {
9334  array = create<array_t>();
9335  break;
9336  }
9337 
9338  case value_t::string: {
9339  string = create<string_t>("");
9340  break;
9341  }
9342 
9343  case value_t::boolean: {
9344  boolean = boolean_t(false);
9345  break;
9346  }
9347 
9348  case value_t::number_integer: {
9349  number_integer = number_integer_t(0);
9350  break;
9351  }
9352 
9353  case value_t::number_unsigned: {
9354  number_unsigned = number_unsigned_t(0);
9355  break;
9356  }
9357 
9358  case value_t::number_float: {
9359  number_float = number_float_t(0.0);
9360  break;
9361  }
9362 
9363  case value_t::null: {
9364  object = nullptr; // silence warning, see #821
9365  break;
9366  }
9367 
9368  default: {
9369  object = nullptr; // silence warning, see #821
9370  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(t == value_t::null)) {
9371  JSON_THROW(other_error::create(500, "961c151d2e87f2686a955a9be24d316f1362bf21 3.1.0")); // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
9372  }
9373  break;
9374  }
9375  }
9376  }
9377 
9379  json_value(const string_t &value) {
9380  string = create<string_t>(value);
9381  }
9382 
9384  json_value(string_t &&value) {
9385  string = create<string_t>(std::move(value));
9386  }

9395  object = create<object_t>(std::move(value));

9408  void destroy(value_t t) noexcept {
9409  switch (t) {
9410  case value_t::object: {
9411  AllocatorType<object_t> alloc;
9412  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, object);
9413  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, object, 1);
9414  break;
9415  }
9416 
9417  case value_t::array: {
9418  AllocatorType<array_t> alloc;
9419  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, array);
9420  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, array, 1);
9421  break;
9422  }
9423 
9424  case value_t::string: {
9425  AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
9426  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, string);
9427  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, string, 1);
9428  break;
9429  }
9430 
9431  default: { break; }
9432  }
9433  }
9434  };

9649  template <typename CompatibleType, typename U = detail::uncvref_t<CompatibleType>,
9650  detail::enable_if_t<detail::is_compatible_type<basic_json_t, U>::value, int> = 0>

9731  basic_json(initializer_list_t init, bool type_deduction = true, value_t manual_type = value_t::array) {
9732  // check if each element is an array with two elements whose first
9733  // element is a string
9734  bool is_an_object = std::all_of(init.begin(), init.end(), [](const detail::json_ref<basic_json> &element_ref) {
9735  return (element_ref->is_array() and element_ref->size() == 2 and (*element_ref)[0].is_string());
9736  });
9737 
9738  // adjust type if type deduction is not wanted
9739  if (not type_deduction) {
9740  // if array is wanted, do not create an object though possible
9741  if (manual_type == value_t::array) {
9742  is_an_object = false;
9743  }
9744 
9745  // if object is wanted but impossible, throw an exception
9746  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(manual_type == value_t::object and not is_an_object)) {
9747  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(301, "cannot create object from initializer list"));
9748  }
9749  }
9750 
9751  if (is_an_object) {
9752  // the initializer list is a list of pairs -> create object
9753  m_type = value_t::object;
9754  m_value = value_t::object;
9755 
9756  std::for_each(init.begin(), init.end(), [this](const detail::json_ref<basic_json> &element_ref) {
9757  auto element = element_ref.moved_or_copied();
9758  m_value.object->emplace(std::move(*((*element.m_value.array)[0].m_value.string)),
9759  std::move((*element.m_value.array)[1]));
9760  });
9761  } else {
9762  // the initializer list describes an array -> create array
9763  m_type = value_t::array;
9764  m_value.array = create<array_t>(init.begin(), init.end());
9765  }
9766 
9767  assert_invariant();
9768  }
9769 
9807  static basic_json array(initializer_list_t init = {}) {
9808  return basic_json(init, false, value_t::array);
9809  }
9810 
9849  static basic_json object(initializer_list_t init = {}) {
9850  return basic_json(init, false, value_t::object);
9851  }

9875  basic_json(size_type cnt, const basic_json &val) : m_type(value_t::array) {
9876  m_value.array = create<array_t>(cnt, val);
9877  assert_invariant();
9878  }

9935  template <class InputIT,
9936  typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<InputIT, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
9937  std::is_same<InputIT, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value,
9938  int>::type = 0>
9939  basic_json(InputIT first, InputIT last) {
9940  assert(first.m_object != nullptr);
9941  assert(last.m_object != nullptr);
9942 
9943  // make sure iterator fits the current value
9944  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object)) {
9945  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(201, "iterators are not compatible"));
9946  }
9947 
9948  // copy type from first iterator
9949  m_type = first.m_object->m_type;
9950 
9951  // check if iterator range is complete for primitive values
9952  switch (m_type) {
9953  case value_t::boolean:
9954  case value_t::number_float:
9955  case value_t::number_integer:
9956  case value_t::number_unsigned:
9957  case value_t::string: {
9958  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not first.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin() or not last.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_end())) {
9959  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(204, "iterators out of range"));
9960  }
9961  break;
9962  }
9963 
9964  default:
9965  break;
9966  }
9967 
9968  switch (m_type) {
9969  case value_t::number_integer: {
9970  m_value.number_integer = first.m_object->m_value.number_integer;
9971  break;
9972  }
9973 
9974  case value_t::number_unsigned: {
9975  m_value.number_unsigned = first.m_object->m_value.number_unsigned;
9976  break;
9977  }
9978 
9979  case value_t::number_float: {
9980  m_value.number_float = first.m_object->m_value.number_float;
9981  break;
9982  }
9983 
9984  case value_t::boolean: {
9985  m_value.boolean = first.m_object->m_value.boolean;
9986  break;
9987  }
9988 
9989  case value_t::string: {
9990  m_value = *first.m_object->m_value.string;
9991  break;
9992  }
9993 
9994  case value_t::object: {
9995  m_value.object = create<object_t>(first.m_it.object_iterator, last.m_it.object_iterator);
9996  break;
9997  }
9998 
9999  case value_t::array: {
10000  m_value.array = create<array_t>(first.m_it.array_iterator, last.m_it.array_iterator);
10001  break;
10002  }
10003 
10004  default:
10005  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(206, "cannot construct with iterators from " +
10006  std::string(first.m_object->type_name())));
10007  }
10008 
10009  assert_invariant();
10010  }

10018  }

10702  template <typename ReferenceType, typename ThisType>
10703  static ReferenceType get_ref_impl(ThisType &obj) {
10704  // delegate the call to get_ptr<>()
10705  auto ptr = obj.template get_ptr<typename std::add_pointer<ReferenceType>::type>();
10706 
10707  if (JSON_LIKELY(ptr != nullptr)) {
10708  return *ptr;
10709  }
10710 
10711  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(303, "incompatible ReferenceType for get_ref, actual type is " +
10712  std::string(obj.type_name())));
10713  }

10734  template <typename BasicJsonType,
10735  detail::enable_if_t<std::is_same<typename std::remove_const<BasicJsonType>::type, basic_json_t>::value,
10736  int> = 0>
10737  basic_json get() const {
10738  return *this;
10739  }
10740 
10780  template <typename ValueTypeCV, typename ValueType = detail::uncvref_t<ValueTypeCV>,
10781  detail::enable_if_t<not std::is_same<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value and
10782  detail::has_from_json<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value and
10783  not detail::has_non_default_from_json<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value,
10784  int> = 0>
10785  ValueType get() const noexcept(noexcept(JSONSerializer<ValueType>::from_json(std::declval<const basic_json_t &>(),
10786  std::declval<ValueType &>()))) {
10787  // we cannot static_assert on ValueTypeCV being non-const, because
10788  // there is support for get<const basic_json_t>(), which is why we
10789  // still need the uncvref
10790  static_assert(not std::is_reference<ValueTypeCV>::value,
10791  "get() cannot be used with reference types, you might want to use get_ref()");
10792  static_assert(std::is_default_constructible<ValueType>::value,
10793  "types must be DefaultConstructible when used with get()");
10794 
10795  ValueType ret;
10796  JSONSerializer<ValueType>::from_json(*this, ret);
10797  return ret;
10798  }

10831  template <typename ValueTypeCV, typename ValueType = detail::uncvref_t<ValueTypeCV>,
10832  detail::enable_if_t<not std::is_same<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value and
10833  detail::has_non_default_from_json<basic_json_t, ValueType>::value,
10834  int> = 0>
10835  ValueType get() const
10836  noexcept(noexcept(JSONSerializer<ValueTypeCV>::from_json(std::declval<const basic_json_t &>()))) {
10837  static_assert(not std::is_reference<ValueTypeCV>::value,
10838  "get() cannot be used with reference types, you might want to use get_ref()");
10839  return JSONSerializer<ValueTypeCV>::from_json(*this);
10840  }

10911  template <typename PointerType, typename std::enable_if<std::is_pointer<PointerType>::value, int>::type = 0>
10912  PointerType get_ptr() noexcept {
10913  // get the type of the PointerType (remove pointer and const)
10914  using pointee_t = typename std::remove_const<
10915  typename std::remove_pointer<typename std::remove_const<PointerType>::type>::type>::type;
10916  // make sure the type matches the allowed types
10917  static_assert(std::is_same<object_t, pointee_t>::value or std::is_same<array_t, pointee_t>::value or
10918  std::is_same<string_t, pointee_t>::value or std::is_same<boolean_t, pointee_t>::value or
10919  std::is_same<number_integer_t, pointee_t>::value or
10920  std::is_same<number_unsigned_t, pointee_t>::value or
10921  std::is_same<number_float_t, pointee_t>::value,
10922  "incompatible pointer type");
10923 
10924  // delegate the call to get_impl_ptr<>()
10925  return get_impl_ptr(static_cast<PointerType>(nullptr));
10926  }
10927 
10932  template <typename PointerType,
10933  typename std::enable_if<std::is_pointer<PointerType>::value and
10934  std::is_const<typename std::remove_pointer<PointerType>::type>::value,
10935  int>::type = 0>
10936  constexpr const PointerType get_ptr() const noexcept {
10937  // get the type of the PointerType (remove pointer and const)
10938  using pointee_t = typename std::remove_const<
10939  typename std::remove_pointer<typename std::remove_const<PointerType>::type>::type>::type;
10940  // make sure the type matches the allowed types
10941  static_assert(std::is_same<object_t, pointee_t>::value or std::is_same<array_t, pointee_t>::value or
10942  std::is_same<string_t, pointee_t>::value or std::is_same<boolean_t, pointee_t>::value or
10943  std::is_same<number_integer_t, pointee_t>::value or
10944  std::is_same<number_unsigned_t, pointee_t>::value or
10945  std::is_same<number_float_t, pointee_t>::value,
10946  "incompatible pointer type");
10947 
10948  // delegate the call to get_impl_ptr<>() const
10949  return get_impl_ptr(static_cast<PointerType>(nullptr));
10950  }

11263  m_value.array->insert(m_value.array->end(), idx - m_value.array->size() + 1, basic_json());

11735  template <class IteratorType,
11736  typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
11737  std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value,
11738  int>::type = 0>
11739  IteratorType erase(IteratorType pos) {
11740  // make sure iterator fits the current value
11741  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(this != pos.m_object)) {
11742  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
11743  }
11744 
11745  IteratorType result = end();
11746 
11747  switch (m_type) {
11748  case value_t::boolean:
11749  case value_t::number_float:
11750  case value_t::number_integer:
11751  case value_t::number_unsigned:
11752  case value_t::string: {
11753  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not pos.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin())) {
11754  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(205, "iterator out of range"));
11755  }
11756 
11757  if (is_string()) {
11758  AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
11759  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, m_value.string);
11760  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, m_value.string, 1);
11761  m_value.string = nullptr;
11762  }
11763 
11764  m_type = value_t::null;
11765  assert_invariant();
11766  break;
11767  }
11768 
11769  case value_t::object: {
11770  result.m_it.object_iterator = m_value.object->erase(pos.m_it.object_iterator);
11771  break;
11772  }
11773 
11774  case value_t::array: {
11775  result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->erase(pos.m_it.array_iterator);
11776  break;
11777  }
11778 
11779  default:
11780  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(307, "cannot use erase() with " + std::string(type_name())));
11781  }
11782 
11783  return result;
11784  }
11785 
11832  template <class IteratorType,
11833  typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::iterator>::value or
11834  std::is_same<IteratorType, typename basic_json_t::const_iterator>::value,
11835  int>::type = 0>
11836  IteratorType erase(IteratorType first, IteratorType last) {
11837  // make sure iterator fits the current value
11838  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(this != first.m_object or this != last.m_object)) {
11839  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(203, "iterators do not fit current value"));
11840  }
11841 
11842  IteratorType result = end();
11843 
11844  switch (m_type) {
11845  case value_t::boolean:
11846  case value_t::number_float:
11847  case value_t::number_integer:
11848  case value_t::number_unsigned:
11849  case value_t::string: {
11850  if (JSON_LIKELY(not first.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_begin() or not last.m_it.primitive_iterator.is_end())) {
11851  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(204, "iterators out of range"));
11852  }
11853 
11854  if (is_string()) {
11855  AllocatorType<string_t> alloc;
11856  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::destroy(alloc, m_value.string);
11857  std::allocator_traits<decltype(alloc)>::deallocate(alloc, m_value.string, 1);
11858  m_value.string = nullptr;
11859  }
11860 
11861  m_type = value_t::null;
11862  assert_invariant();
11863  break;
11864  }
11865 
11866  case value_t::object: {
11867  result.m_it.object_iterator = m_value.object->erase(first.m_it.object_iterator, last.m_it.object_iterator);
11868  break;
11869  }
11870 
11871  case value_t::array: {
11872  result.m_it.array_iterator = m_value.array->erase(first.m_it.array_iterator, last.m_it.array_iterator);
11873  break;
11874  }
11875 
11876  default:
11877  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(307, "cannot use erase() with " + std::string(type_name())));
11878  }
11879 
11880  return result;
11881  }

12752  void push_back(basic_json &&val) {
12753  // push_back only works for null objects or arrays
12754  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array()))) {
12755  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(308, "cannot use push_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
12756  }
12757 
12758  // transform null object into an array
12759  if (is_null()) {
12760  m_type = value_t::array;
12761  m_value = value_t::array;
12762  assert_invariant();
12763  }
12764 
12765  // add element to array (move semantics)
12766  m_value.array->push_back(std::move(val));
12767  // invalidate object
12768  val.m_type = value_t::null;
12769  }

12778  }

12851  reference operator+=(const typename object_t::value_type &val) {
12852  push_back(val);
12853  return *this;
12854  }

12881  void push_back(initializer_list_t init) {
12882  if (is_object() and init.size() == 2 and (*init.begin())->is_string()) {
12883  basic_json &&key = init.begin()->moved_or_copied();
12884  push_back(
12885  typename object_t::value_type(std::move(key.get_ref<string_t &>()), (init.begin() + 1)->moved_or_copied()));
12886  } else {
12887  push_back(basic_json(init));
12888  }
12889  }
12890 
12895  reference operator+=(initializer_list_t init) {
12896  push_back(init);
12897  return *this;
12898  }

12921  template <class... Args>
12922  void emplace_back(Args &&... args) {
12923  // emplace_back only works for null objects or arrays
12924  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_array()))) {
12925  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(311, "cannot use emplace_back() with " + std::string(type_name())));
12926  }
12927 
12928  // transform null object into an array
12929  if (is_null()) {
12930  m_type = value_t::array;
12931  m_value = value_t::array;
12932  assert_invariant();
12933  }
12934 
12935  // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
12936  m_value.array->emplace_back(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
12937  }
12938 
12966  template <class... Args>
12967  std::pair<iterator, bool> emplace(Args &&... args) {
12968  // emplace only works for null objects or arrays
12969  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not(is_null() or is_object()))) {
12970  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(311, "cannot use emplace() with " + std::string(type_name())));
12971  }
12972 
12973  // transform null object into an object
12974  if (is_null()) {
12975  m_type = value_t::object;
12976  m_value = value_t::object;
12977  assert_invariant();
12978  }
12979 
12980  // add element to array (perfect forwarding)
12981  auto res = m_value.object->emplace(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
12982  // create result iterator and set iterator to the result of emplace
12983  auto it = begin();
12984  it.m_it.object_iterator = res.first;
12985 
12986  // return pair of iterator and boolean
12987  return {it, res.second};
12988  }

13023  return result;

13027  }

13108  iterator insert(const_iterator pos, const_iterator first, const_iterator last) {
13109  // insert only works for arrays
13110  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_array())) {
13111  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(309, "cannot use insert() with " + std::string(type_name())));
13112  }
13113 
13114  // check if iterator pos fits to this JSON value
13115  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(pos.m_object != this)) {
13116  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterator does not fit current value"));
13117  }
13118 
13119  // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
13120  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object)) {
13121  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
13122  }
13123 
13124  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object == this)) {
13125  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(211, "passed iterators may not belong to container"));
13126  }
13127 
13128  // insert to array and return iterator
13129  iterator result(this);
13130  result.m_it.array_iterator =
13131  m_value.array->insert(pos.m_it.array_iterator, first.m_it.array_iterator, last.m_it.array_iterator);
13132  return result;
13133  }

13237  void update(const_reference j) {
13238  // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
13239  if (is_null()) {
13240  m_type = value_t::object;
13241  m_value.object = create<object_t>();
13242  assert_invariant();
13243  }
13244 
13245  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_object())) {
13246  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(type_name())));
13247  }
13248  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not j.is_object())) {
13249  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(j.type_name())));
13250  }
13251 
13252  for (auto it = j.cbegin(); it != j.cend(); ++it) {
13253  m_value.object->operator[](it.key()) = it.value();
13254  }
13255  }
13256 
13283  void update(const_iterator first, const_iterator last) {
13284  // implicitly convert null value to an empty object
13285  if (is_null()) {
13286  m_type = value_t::object;
13287  m_value.object = create<object_t>();
13288  assert_invariant();
13289  }
13290 
13291  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not is_object())) {
13292  JSON_THROW(type_error::create(312, "cannot use update() with " + std::string(type_name())));
13293  }
13294 
13295  // check if range iterators belong to the same JSON object
13296  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(first.m_object != last.m_object)) {
13297  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(210, "iterators do not fit"));
13298  }
13299 
13300  // passed iterators must belong to objects
13301  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not first.m_object->is_object() or not first.m_object->is_object())) {
13302  JSON_THROW(invalid_iterator::create(202, "iterators first and last must point to objects"));
13303  }
13304 
13305  for (auto it = first; it != last; ++it) {
13306  m_value.object->operator[](it.key()) = it.value();
13307  }
13308  }

13432 
13472  friend bool operator==(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept {
13473  const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
13474  const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
13475 
13476  if (lhs_type == rhs_type) {
13477  switch (lhs_type) {
13478  case value_t::array:
13479  return (*lhs.m_value.array == *rhs.m_value.array);
13480 
13481  case value_t::object:
13482  return (*lhs.m_value.object == *rhs.m_value.object);
13483 
13484  case value_t::null:
13485  return true;
13486 
13487  case value_t::string:
13488  return (*lhs.m_value.string == *rhs.m_value.string);
13489 
13490  case value_t::boolean:
13491  return (lhs.m_value.boolean == rhs.m_value.boolean);
13492 
13493  case value_t::number_integer:
13494  return (lhs.m_value.number_integer == rhs.m_value.number_integer);
13495 
13496  case value_t::number_unsigned:
13497  return (lhs.m_value.number_unsigned == rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
13498 
13499  case value_t::number_float:
13500  return (lhs.m_value.number_float == rhs.m_value.number_float);
13501 
13502  default:
13503  return false;
13504  }
13505  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
13506  return (static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) == rhs.m_value.number_float);
13507  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
13508  return (lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer));
13509  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
13510  return (static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_float);
13511  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
13512  return (lhs.m_value.number_float == static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned));
13513  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
13514  return (static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) == rhs.m_value.number_integer);
13515  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
13516  return (lhs.m_value.number_integer == static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned));
13517  }
13518 
13519  return false;
13520  }

13606  friend bool operator<(const_reference lhs, const_reference rhs) noexcept {
13607  const auto lhs_type = lhs.type();
13608  const auto rhs_type = rhs.type();
13609 
13610  if (lhs_type == rhs_type) {
13611  switch (lhs_type) {
13612  case value_t::array:
13613  return (*lhs.m_value.array) < (*rhs.m_value.array);
13614 
13615  case value_t::object:
13616  return *lhs.m_value.object < *rhs.m_value.object;
13617 
13618  case value_t::null:
13619  return false;
13620 
13621  case value_t::string:
13622  return *lhs.m_value.string < *rhs.m_value.string;
13623 
13624  case value_t::boolean:
13625  return lhs.m_value.boolean < rhs.m_value.boolean;
13626 
13627  case value_t::number_integer:
13628  return lhs.m_value.number_integer < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
13629 
13630  case value_t::number_unsigned:
13631  return lhs.m_value.number_unsigned < rhs.m_value.number_unsigned;
13632 
13633  case value_t::number_float:
13634  return lhs.m_value.number_float < rhs.m_value.number_float;
13635 
13636  default:
13637  return false;
13638  }
13639  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
13640  return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_integer) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
13641  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
13642  return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_integer);
13643  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_float) {
13644  return static_cast<number_float_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_float;
13645  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_float and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
13646  return lhs.m_value.number_float < static_cast<number_float_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
13647  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_integer and rhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned) {
13648  return lhs.m_value.number_integer < static_cast<number_integer_t>(rhs.m_value.number_unsigned);
13649  } else if (lhs_type == value_t::number_unsigned and rhs_type == value_t::number_integer) {
13650  return static_cast<number_integer_t>(lhs.m_value.number_unsigned) < rhs.m_value.number_integer;
13651  }
13652 
13653  // We only reach this line if we cannot compare values. In that case,
13654  // we compare types. Note we have to call the operator explicitly,
13655  // because MSVC has problems otherwise.
13656  return operator<(lhs_type, rhs_type);
13657  }

13840  friend std::ostream &operator<<(std::ostream &o, const basic_json &j) {
13841  // read width member and use it as indentation parameter if nonzero
13842  const bool pretty_print = (o.width() > 0);
13843  const auto indentation = (pretty_print ? o.width() : 0);
13844 
13845  // reset width to 0 for subsequent calls to this stream
13846  o.width(0);
13847 
13848  // do the actual serialization
13849  serializer s(detail::output_adapter<char>(o), o.fill());
13850  s.dump(j, pretty_print, false, static_cast<unsigned int>(indentation));
13851  return o;
13852  }

14920  // JSON Patch functions //
14922 
14925 
14973  basic_json patch(const basic_json &json_patch) const {
14974  // make a working copy to apply the patch to
14975  basic_json result = *this;
14976 
14977  // the valid JSON Patch operations
14978  enum class patch_operations { add, remove, replace, move, copy, test, invalid };
14979 
14980  const auto get_op = [](const std::string &op) {
14981  if (op == "add") {
14982  return patch_operations::add;
14983  }
14984  if (op == "remove") {
14985  return patch_operations::remove;
14986  }
14987  if (op == "replace") {
14988  return patch_operations::replace;
14989  }
14990  if (op == "move") {
14991  return patch_operations::move;
14992  }
14993  if (op == "copy") {
14994  return patch_operations::copy;
14995  }
14996  if (op == "test") {
14997  return patch_operations::test;
14998  }
14999 
15000  return patch_operations::invalid;
15001  };
15002 
15003  // wrapper for "add" operation; add value at ptr
15004  const auto operation_add = [&result](json_pointer &ptr, basic_json val) {
15005  // adding to the root of the target document means replacing it
15006  if (ptr.is_root()) {
15007  result = val;
15008  } else {
15009  // make sure the top element of the pointer exists
15010  json_pointer top_pointer = ptr.top();
15011  if (top_pointer != ptr) {
15012  result.at(top_pointer);
15013  }
15014 
15015  // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
15016  const auto last_path = ptr.pop_back();
15017  basic_json &parent = result[ptr];
15018 
15019  switch (parent.m_type) {
15020  case value_t::null:
15021  case value_t::object: {
15022  // use operator[] to add value
15023  parent[last_path] = val;
15024  break;
15025  }
15026 
15027  case value_t::array: {
15028  if (last_path == "-") {
15029  // special case: append to back
15030  parent.push_back(val);
15031  } else {
15032  const auto idx = json_pointer::array_index(last_path);
15033  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(static_cast<size_type>(idx) > parent.size())) {
15034  // avoid undefined behavior
15035  JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(401, "array index " + std::to_string(idx) + " is out of range"));
15036  } else {
15037  // default case: insert add offset
15038  parent.insert(parent.begin() + static_cast<difference_type>(idx), val);
15039  }
15040  }
15041  break;
15042  }
15043 
15044  default: {
15045  // if there exists a parent it cannot be primitive
15046  assert(false); // LCOV_EXCL_LINE
15047  }
15048  }
15049  }
15050  };
15051 
15052  // wrapper for "remove" operation; remove value at ptr
15053  const auto operation_remove = [&result](json_pointer &ptr) {
15054  // get reference to parent of JSON pointer ptr
15055  const auto last_path = ptr.pop_back();
15056  basic_json &parent = result.at(ptr);
15057 
15058  // remove child
15059  if (parent.is_object()) {
15060  // perform range check
15061  auto it = parent.find(last_path);
15062  if (JSON_LIKELY(it != parent.end())) {
15063  parent.erase(it);
15064  } else {
15065  JSON_THROW(out_of_range::create(403, "key '" + last_path + "' not found"));
15066  }
15067  } else if (parent.is_array()) {
15068  // note erase performs range check
15069  parent.erase(static_cast<size_type>(json_pointer::array_index(last_path)));
15070  }
15071  };
15072 
15073  // type check: top level value must be an array
15074  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not json_patch.is_array())) {
15075  JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(104, 0, "JSON patch must be an array of objects"));
15076  }
15077 
15078  // iterate and apply the operations
15079  for (const auto &val : json_patch) {
15080  // wrapper to get a value for an operation
15081  const auto get_value = [&val](const std::string &op, const std::string &member,
15082  bool string_type) -> basic_json & {
15083  // find value
15084  auto it = val.m_value.object->find(member);
15085 
15086  // context-sensitive error message
15087  const auto error_msg = (op == "op") ? "operation" : "operation '" + op + "'";
15088 
15089  // check if desired value is present
15090  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(it == val.m_value.object->end())) {
15091  JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, error_msg + " must have member '" + member + "'"));
15092  }
15093 
15094  // check if result is of type string
15095  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(string_type and not it->second.is_string())) {
15096  JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, error_msg + " must have string member '" + member + "'"));
15097  }
15098 
15099  // no error: return value
15100  return it->second;
15101  };
15102 
15103  // type check: every element of the array must be an object
15104  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not val.is_object())) {
15105  JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(104, 0, "JSON patch must be an array of objects"));
15106  }
15107 
15108  // collect mandatory members
15109  const std::string op = get_value("op", "op", true);
15110  const std::string path = get_value(op, "path", true);
15111  json_pointer ptr(path);
15112 
15113  switch (get_op(op)) {
15114  case patch_operations::add: {
15115  operation_add(ptr, get_value("add", "value", false));
15116  break;
15117  }
15118 
15119  case patch_operations::remove: {
15120  operation_remove(ptr);
15121  break;
15122  }
15123 
15124  case patch_operations::replace: {
15125  // the "path" location must exist - use at()
15126  result.at(ptr) = get_value("replace", "value", false);
15127  break;
15128  }
15129 
15130  case patch_operations::move: {
15131  const std::string from_path = get_value("move", "from", true);
15132  json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
15133 
15134  // the "from" location must exist - use at()
15135  basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
15136 
15137  // The move operation is functionally identical to a
15138  // "remove" operation on the "from" location, followed
15139  // immediately by an "add" operation at the target
15140  // location with the value that was just removed.
15141  operation_remove(from_ptr);
15142  operation_add(ptr, v);
15143  break;
15144  }
15145 
15146  case patch_operations::copy: {
15147  const std::string from_path = get_value("copy", "from", true);
15148  const json_pointer from_ptr(from_path);
15149 
15150  // the "from" location must exist - use at()
15151  basic_json v = result.at(from_ptr);
15152 
15153  // The copy is functionally identical to an "add"
15154  // operation at the target location using the value
15155  // specified in the "from" member.
15156  operation_add(ptr, v);
15157  break;
15158  }
15159 
15160  case patch_operations::test: {
15161  bool success = false;
15162  JSON_TRY {
15163  // check if "value" matches the one at "path"
15164  // the "path" location must exist - use at()
15165  success = (result.at(ptr) == get_value("test", "value", false));
15166  }
15167  JSON_CATCH(out_of_range &) {
15168  // ignore out of range errors: success remains false
15169  }
15170 
15171  // throw an exception if test fails
15172  if (JSON_UNLIKELY(not success)) {
15173  JSON_THROW(other_error::create(501, "unsuccessful: " + val.dump()));
15174  }
15175 
15176  break;
15177  }
15178 
15179  case patch_operations::invalid: {
15180  // op must be "add", "remove", "replace", "move", "copy", or
15181  // "test"
15182  JSON_THROW(parse_error::create(105, 0, "operation value '" + op + "' is invalid"));
15183  }
15184  }
15185  }
15186 
15187  return result;
15188  }
15189 
15223  static basic_json diff(const basic_json &source, const basic_json &target, const std::string &path = "") {
15224  // the patch
15225  basic_json result(value_t::array);
15226 
15227  // if the values are the same, return empty patch
15228  if (source == target) {
15229  return result;
15230  }
15231 
15232  if (source.type() != target.type()) {
15233  // different types: replace value
15234  result.push_back({{"op", "replace"}, {"path", path}, {"value", target}});
15235  } else {
15236  switch (source.type()) {
15237  case value_t::array: {
15238  // first pass: traverse common elements
15239  std::size_t i = 0;
15240  while (i < source.size() and i < target.size()) {
15241  // recursive call to compare array values at index i
15242  auto temp_diff = diff(source[i], target[i], path + "/" + std::to_string(i));
15243  result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
15244  ++i;
15245  }
15246 
15247  // i now reached the end of at least one array
15248  // in a second pass, traverse the remaining elements
15249 
15250  // remove my remaining elements
15251  const auto end_index = static_cast<difference_type>(result.size());
15252  while (i < source.size()) {
15253  // add operations in reverse order to avoid invalid
15254  // indices
15255  result.insert(result.begin() + end_index,
15256  object({{"op", "remove"}, {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)}}));
15257  ++i;
15258  }
15259 
15260  // add other remaining elements
15261  while (i < target.size()) {
15262  result.push_back({{"op", "add"}, {"path", path + "/" + std::to_string(i)}, {"value", target[i]}});
15263  ++i;
15264  }
15265 
15266  break;
15267  }
15268 
15269  case value_t::object: {
15270  // first pass: traverse this object's elements
15271  for (auto it = source.cbegin(); it != source.cend(); ++it) {
15272  // escape the key name to be used in a JSON patch
15273  const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
15274 
15275  if (target.find(it.key()) != target.end()) {
15276  // recursive call to compare object values at key it
15277  auto temp_diff = diff(it.value(), target[it.key()], path + "/" + key);
15278  result.insert(result.end(), temp_diff.begin(), temp_diff.end());
15279  } else {
15280  // found a key that is not in o -> remove it
15281  result.push_back(object({{"op", "remove"}, {"path", path + "/" + key}}));
15282  }
15283  }
15284 
15285  // second pass: traverse other object's elements
15286  for (auto it = target.cbegin(); it != target.cend(); ++it) {
15287  if (source.find(it.key()) == source.end()) {
15288  // found a key that is not in this -> add it
15289  const auto key = json_pointer::escape(it.key());
15290  result.push_back({{"op", "add"}, {"path", path + "/" + key}, {"value", it.value()}});
15291  }
15292  }
15293 
15294  break;
15295  }
15296 
15297  default: {
15298  // both primitive type: replace value
15299  result.push_back({{"op", "replace"}, {"path", path}, {"value", target}});
15300  break;
15301  }
15302  }
15303  }
15304 
15305  return result;
15306  }

15311  // JSON Merge Patch functions //
15313 
15316 
15359  void merge_patch(const basic_json &patch) {
15360  if (patch.is_object()) {
15361  if (not is_object()) {
15362  *this = object();
15363  }
15364  for (auto it = patch.begin(); it != patch.end(); ++it) {
15365  if (it.value().is_null()) {
15366  erase(it.key());
15367  } else {
15368  operator[](it.key()).merge_patch(it.value());
15369  }
15370  }
15371  } else {
15372  *this = patch;
15373  }
15374  }
15375 
15377  };
